</augment_code_snippet>

**The Error:**
The `pop()` method returns the **removed element** (which is a number), not an array. So `arr3` contains the value `5`, not an array. When you try to call `arr3.concat(arr2)` on line 70, you're trying to call the `concat()` method on a number, which will cause a TypeError because numbers don't have a `concat()` method.

**The Fix:**
If you want to remove the last element from `arr1` and then concatenate the modified array with `arr2`, you should do:

```javascript
const arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const arr2 = [5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10];
arr1.pop(); // This removes the last element (5) from arr1
x = arr1.concat(arr2); // Now arr1 is [1, 2, 3, 4] and gets concatenated with arr2
```

Or if you want to keep the original arrays unchanged:

```javascript
const arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const arr2 = [5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10];
const arr3 = [...arr1]; // Create a copy
arr3.pop(); // Remove last element from the copy
x = arr3.concat(arr2);
```

The error occurs because `pop()` returns the removed element, not the modified array.
